<br>
What are some solo strategies for mid levels? What are the best weapons and armor? Do you think Paladins are most effective solo or in groups?<br>
<br>
I'm a lvl 40 Dwarf Paladin (Just joined TF) and I prefer to group, because I can't pull fast enough solo to make as much exp. Even if it comes to pulling the same mobs with a group, I still get more exp because we can pull continuously and there's no down time for healing.<br>
<br>
When I solo, I like to use Yaulp II and cease, desist and stun while I attack to knock the bad guys flat. And, of course, I root and heal a lot.<br>
<br>
Anybody else know some good tactics?<br>
<br>
Cheers,<br>
Brarris Bonecutter<br>
Paladin of Underfoot <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/btribalfury31319.showUserPublicProfile?gid=polarinferno>PolarInferno</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 30<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/03 2:43:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ftribalfury31319frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Woot for Pallies.</span><hr size=1> Blind is a great tool for stripping mobs off casters.<br>
<br>
Run up to the mob, start whacking/taunting and toss a blind on it too. Once its blind, the caster can back up safely usually. Just be sure to not try and pull the mob anywhere until the blind wears off, or it will just run around aimlessly, or hit anyone else that's in immediate melee range.<br>
<br>
I only have a 23 pally, but I've been using this strat from level 9 and it works pretty nicely <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/btribalfury31319.showUserPublicProfile?gid=brarris>Brarris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/10/03 4:57:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ftribalfury31319frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> That seems like a good plan.</span><hr size=1> Putting a Flash of Light on a caster seems like a good idea. Ever tried it in a duel? I'll have to see if that works to incapacitate a giant also, because stun does not. I don't have Flash of Light atm, but I'll have to get it now that you've brought my attention to that.<br>
<br>
When I began playing my Paladin (This is my first and only character) I was a bit dumb when it came to spell strategy and I didn't fill out my low level spells.<br>
<br>
For example, I never knew how valuable Cease and Desist were until level 35 or so. I was basically using my Paladin like a weak warrior with heal spells and rooting ability.<br>
<br>
At level 39 I figured out how chain stuns and all that good stuff work and have since turned into a heavily armed and armored cleric. If you have enough mana to be a healer, you can do really well playing medic for a group. Especially since, if you draw aggro, your party doesn't have to freak out because you can just klonk the mob in the head and go back to casting -- unlike a typical cleric which would have to root and run.<br>
<br>
You do have to have the patience to sit and med through the fights though, 'cuz you can't build enough mana to keep a group alive if you're swinging an axe all the time.<br>
<br>
Brarris Bonecutter<br>
Paladin of Underfoot<br>
